{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524942"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:10:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:10:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14040"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14040"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.53,0.19,0.07,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92625"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6689"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14040"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75966"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"2650"},{"type":"tags","id":"2779"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43470"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92625"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 86-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a first episode of syncope. He has a medical history of benign prostatic hyperplasia, hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, heart failure with reduced ejection fraction, and hypercholesterolaemia. He lives at home with his wife and is fully independent, using a walking stick for mobility. His medications include tamsulosin/dutasteride, perindopril, furosemide, hydrochlorothiazide, metformin, sitagliptin, empagliflozin, and insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg supine, dropping to 102/65 mmHg on standing, and SpO2 96% on room air. Cardiovascular examination reveals dual heart sounds with no added sounds or murmurs. Respiratory examination is unremarkable. There is no peripheral oedema. Neurological examination reveals no focal deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management to reduce postural hypotension in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discontinue perindopril","Discontinue tamsulosin","Commence fludrocortisone","Commence midodrine","Increase frusemide dose"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in managing this patient\u0027s postural hypotension is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ediscontinue tamsulosin\u003C/strong\u003E. Tamsulosin is an alpha-1 antagonist commonly used for benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), but it is also a frequent contributor to orthostatic hypotension in older adults. In this case, reviewing and adjusting current medications, particularly those known to cause postural hypotension, is the best first-line approach. The dutasteride component of combination therapy for BPH can be continued to avoid lower urinary tract symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscontinuing perindopril\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate approach, as it is less implicated in postural hypotension than alpha-1 antagonists. While ACE inhibitors can contribute to postural hypotension, abruptly stopping this medication could have negative effects on the patient\u0027s blood pressure control and heart failure management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing fludrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best first-line option for this patient. While fludrocortisone can be effective in treating orthostatic hypotension, it works by promoting sodium and fluid retention. This mechanism could potentially exacerbate the patient\u0027s heart failure, making it a less suitable choice without first trying other interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing midodrine\u003C/strong\u003E, an alpha-1 agonist, could be considered if non-pharmacological measures and medication adjustments are insufficient. However, it is not the most appropriate first step, as it introduces a new medication with potential side effects and interactions before optimising the current regimen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the furosemide dose\u003C/strong\u003E would likely worsen the patient\u0027s postural hypotension by causing further volume depletion. This option would be counterproductive in managing the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe best approach is to review and adjust the patient\u0027s current medications, starting with discontinuing tamsulosin. This addresses the underlying cause of the problem while minimising potential side effects and drug interactions in an elderly patient with multiple comorbidities. Other possible options would include monitoring blood pressure longitudinally and considering reduction is dosage of medications such as perindopril, furosemide and hydrochlorothiazide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-pharmacological measures such as compression stockings, adequate hydration, and slow positional changes should also be recommended. If these measures are insufficient, then other pharmacological options could be considered, weighing their potential benefits against risks in the context of the patient\u0027s comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Postural hypotension in older adults often requires a multifaceted approach, including medication review and non-pharmacological measures.","Alpha-1 antagonists like tamsulosin are common contributors to orthostatic hypotension in older adults and should be reviewed when postural symptoms occur.","Medication review and adjustment is the first-line approach for managing postural hypotension in older adults with polypharmacy."],"references":["Rivasi G, Rafanelli M, Mossello E, Brignole M, Ungar A. Drug-Related Orthostatic Hypotension: Beyond Anti-Hypertensive Medications. Drugs Aging. 2020;37(10):725-738. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7524811/","Fedorowski A, Ricci F, Hamrefors V, et al. Orthostatic Hypotension: Management of a Complex, But Common, Medical Problem [published correction appears in Circ Arrhythm Electrophysiol. 2023 Aug;16(8):478. doi: 10.1161/HAE.0000000000000088]. Circ Arrhythm Electrophysiol. 2022;15(3):e010573. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35212554/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75966"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14040"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75966"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T17:10:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T17:10:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6689"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92625"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"